@flexiarg aif/measurement-window-hygiene
@title Measurement-Window Hygiene (Tight Baseline, Settled Readback, Drop the Confounded)
@sigils [⊢⊣/≈]
@keywords measurement, baseline, settled read, transient spike, stale begin, drift, before-after, eventual consistency, prediction error, confound
@audience anyone measuring an action's effect on a drifting, settling system
@tone practical
@style pattern

! conclusion: To measure an action's effect on a system that drifts and settles over time, capture the BASELINE tight — right before the action, not before the preparatory work — and read the EFFECT settled — after the state stabilizes (≥2 consecutive reads agree within ε) — and EXCLUDE any pair where drift or transience confounds the window. A before/after number is only as good as the window it brackets.

  + context: You measure `effect = after − before` around an action, in a system whose state
    propagates asynchronously (scans, caches, eventual consistency, a live field other agents touch).

  + IF:
      You record a predicted/realised (or before/after) pair to score an action's effect on such a
      system.

  + HOWEVER:
      Two window failures inflate or fabricate the number, and both look clean:
      (a) STALE BASELINE — you captured "before" *early* (e.g. before minting the artifact the action
      commits), and the system drifted in between; the measured Δ is mostly that drift, not the action.
      (b) TRANSIENT READBACK — you read "after" at the first post-action sample, catching an in-flight
      spike that decays to baseline; the measured Δ is a scan-timing artifact.

  + THEN:
      Bracket the window tightly. BEFORE: capture the baseline immediately prior to the field-visible
      action — do the preparatory work first, *then* baseline, *then* commit. AFTER: read at the
      settled state — require ≥2 consecutive reads agreeing within ε; tag `:settled` vs `:transient`
      and exclude transient. And if the system drifted independently inside the window, DROP the pair
      (untagged / proposal-mode) rather than attribute the drift to the action.

  + BECAUSE:
      A measurement's validity lives in its window, not its arithmetic. The durable effect is what
      persists between a tight baseline and a settled readback; everything else — drift, spikes — is
      the window leaking. Excluding a confounded pair keeps the dataset honest; recording it launders
      noise as signal. (The two failures, caught live: a 0.277 "move" that was a transient spike
      (retracted on settled re-read); and a 0.277 "move" that was field drift during artifact-minting
      (excluded, proposal-mode) — same magnitude, both fake, both caught by tightening the window.)

  + how-to-apply:
      Order operations: prepare → baseline → act → settle → read → (exclude if confounded). Never
      baseline before the slow part; never read before the fast part settles; never attribute a
      window's drift to the action inside it. Distilled from the FutonZero G-SIM calibration arc
      (WM-pilot, 2026-06-11). Sibling of `[[aif/no-self-certification]]`.
